<section>
<section id="formal-logic">
<h2>Formal Logic</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">A <em>formal logical system</em> is a tool for investigating a specific kind of human reasoning in a rigorous, objective way.</li>
<li class="fragment">Logical systems are defined by the <strong>language</strong> we use to express the statements and rules of the system.</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2 id="defining-the-language">Defining the language</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">All languages have three main components:
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Vocabulary: the basic meaningful units of the language (<em>the words</em>)</li>
<li class="fragment">Syntax: the rules for putting basic units together to form larger meaningful units (<em>the sentences</em>)</li>
<li class="fragment">Semantics: the rules for assigning meanings to the sentences</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">This is true for <em>natural</em> languages (English, Tagalog) as well as the formal languages we will investigate.</li>
<li class="fragment">But formal languages are different in that the rules of the language are <em>rigorously</em> and <em>explicitly</em> laid out before we start using them.</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2 id="kinds-of-vocab">Kinds of vocabulary</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">We divide the vocabulary of a formal language into two parts:</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Logical vocab: the bits that are specific to the logic, and for which we will define specific rules.</li>
<li class="fragment">Nonlogical vocab: the things out in the world that the logic is used to investigate.</li>
</ul>
<li class="fragment">To make the working parts of the language more explicit, we use <strong>symbols</strong> to stand in for complete words.</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Letters (<i>A,B,C,a,b,c,x,y,z...</i>) for nonlogical vocabulary.</li>
<li class="fragment">Special characters (<i>&#x2219;, &#x2228;, &#x2283;, &#x2261;,...) for logical vocabulary.</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Reasoning and arguments</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Logical languages are interesting in their own right. But their main function is to help us explain what makes for good and bad <strong>reasoning</strong>.</li>
<li class="fragment">The primary tool of reasoning is the <strong>argument</strong>, which is a logical defense of a particular claim, or sentence.</li>
<li class="fragment">Arguments involve:</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Premises: one or more sentences used as the foundation of the reasoning.</li>
<li class="fragment">Conclusion: a sentence that is the end point of the reasoning.</li>
<li class="fragment">Support relation: the explanation of how the premises <em>lead to</em> the conclusion.</li>
</ul></ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2 id="using-the-language">Using the language</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Thus, we also need our language to define <em>relations between sentences</em> to explain how good arguments work.</li>
<li class="fragment">Using the components we defined earlier, we can do just that:
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Syntactic relations: ways to <em>transform</em> one sentence into another one.</li>
<li class="fragment">Semantic properties of sentences: <em>tautology</em>, <em>contradiction</em></li>
<li class="fragment">Semantic relations between sentences: <em>equivalence</em>, <em>consequence</em></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2>How this relates to the software tools</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">The textbook includes some software, which provides us with tools for investigating the language.</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Boole: a tool for constructing truth tables. (Investigates semantic properties of sentences)</li>
<li class="fragment">Tarski's world: a tool for constructing "worlds" filled with various objects standing in various relations. (Investigates semantic relations between sentences)</li>
<li class="fragment">Fitch: a tool for constructing proofs in FOL. (Investigates syntactic relations between sentences)</li>
</ul></ul>
</section>

</section>

